    <div class="help-body" id="helpBody">

      <h3 id="h-overview">&#128202; What this tool does</h3>
      <p>This is a point-to-point link planning calculator covering both <strong>Microwave (MW)</strong> bands
      (4&ndash;42&nbsp;GHz) and <strong>millimetre-wave (mmW)</strong> bands (E / W / D-band, 71&ndash;174&nbsp;GHz).
      Enter the radio configuration, antennas, path length and climate; it computes the full <strong>link budget</strong>,
      <strong>rain and multipath outage</strong>, predicted <strong>availability</strong> and <strong>capacity</strong>
      for every supported modulation profile. Real terrain and climate data can be pulled from the map to auto-size
      antenna heights and rain rate.</p>
      <div class="help-note">All propagation maths follows the ITU-R Recommendations listed in the header.
      RSL / TX / capacity tables are Ceragon equipment figures. Results are planning estimates &mdash; always
      confirm against the official datasheet and a field survey before deployment.</div>

      <h3 id="h-quickstart">&#9889; Quick start</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1. Choose mode.</strong> The <em>Band</em> selector at the top determines the mode:
            <strong>Microwave</strong> = 4&ndash;42&nbsp;GHz products; <strong>E / W / D-Band</strong> = mmW products.
            Microwave is listed first.</li>
        <li><strong>2. Pick the product.</strong> For MW select product (IP-20C, IP-50C/CX, RFU-D/D-HP &hellip;),
            frequency band, channel BW and configuration. For mmW select band, product variant and channel BW.</li>
        <li><strong>3. Choose antennas.</strong> Set a dish size for Site A and Site B.</li>
        <li><strong>4. Set the path.</strong> Enter the distance (or pin two sites on the map) and rain zone / rate.</li>
        <li><strong>5. Set your target.</strong> Choose the availability you must meet (e.g. 99.995&nbsp;%).</li>
        <li><strong>6. Read the result.</strong> The status box and modulation table show whether the link meets
            the target and at which modulation, with achievable capacity.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="help-tip">Don&apos;t know the distance or rain rate? Use the <strong>Site Location &amp; Climate</strong>
      map to pin both ends &mdash; distance, terrain profile and ITU-R rain rate are filled in automatically.</div>

      <h3 id="h-radio">&#128251; Radio settings</h3>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><th>Control</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Band</td><td>Master selector. <strong>Microwave</strong> appears first, followed by E-Band, W-Band and D-Band.
            Selecting Microwave reveals the MW-specific settings card; selecting a mmW band shows the mmW controls.
            Changing band resets frequency, bandwidth and product to defaults.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>MW Product</td><td>(MW mode only) Selects the Ceragon radio family:
            <strong>IP-20C</strong> (6&ndash;42&nbsp;GHz), <strong>IP-20C-HP</strong> (4&ndash;11&nbsp;GHz high-power),
            <strong>IP-50C / IP-50CX</strong> (6&ndash;42&nbsp;GHz wide-band), <strong>RFU-D</strong> (6&ndash;42&nbsp;GHz)
            or <strong>RFU-D-HP</strong> (4&ndash;11&nbsp;GHz high-power, <em>10&nbsp;GHz not supported</em>).
            The product determines the available frequency bands, channel BWs, TX power and RSL thresholds.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>MW Frequency Band</td><td>Nominal band in GHz (4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 11, 13, 15, 18, 23, 26, 28, 32, 38, 42 &mdash;
            availability depends on product). IP-20C uses 10.5&nbsp;GHz internally for the 10&nbsp;GHz band.
            IP-50C/CX and IP-20C do not support 4/5&nbsp;GHz; RFU-D-HP supports only 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 11&nbsp;GHz.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Channel BW</td><td>Channel width in MHz. Available options depend on product, band and standard (ETSI / FCC).
            Some combinations are blocked where the product does not support them (e.g. IP-50C cannot use 224&nbsp;MHz at 4/5/7/8&nbsp;GHz).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>mmW Product (E-Band)</td><td>Only shown for E-Band: <strong>IP-50EX(A)</strong> (standard power) or
            <strong>IP-50EX(A)-P</strong> (high power, +3&nbsp;dB TX).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Standard</td><td><strong>ETSI</strong> or <strong>FCC</strong> &mdash; affects channel BW options,
            EIRP assumptions and capacity frame size defaults.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Configuration</td><td><strong>1+0</strong> = single carrier; <strong>2+0</strong> = two carriers
            (doubles capacity, adjusts branching loss); <strong>1+1</strong>, <strong>2+2</strong>, <strong>4+0</strong>
            also available where applicable.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>RSL Performance Level</td><td><strong>Typical</strong> = nominal published sensitivity;
            <strong>Guaranteed</strong> = worst-case conservative (lower fade margin).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>RSL BER Threshold</td><td>BER point for the RSL threshold: <code>10&#8315;&#8310;</code> (stricter)
            or <code>10&#8315;&#179;</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ACM &amp; ACMB</td><td><strong>ACM</strong> = Adaptive Coding &amp; Modulation (link drops to a
            more robust profile during fades). <strong>ACMB</strong> is blocked automatically when MW band is selected
            for products where it is not applicable.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Polarization</td><td><strong>H</strong> or <strong>V</strong>. Vertical polarization suffers
            slightly less rain attenuation.</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h3 id="h-mw">&#128225; Microwave-specific settings</h3>
      <p>When a Microwave band is selected a dedicated <em>Microwave Link Settings</em> card appears with the
      following controls:</p>

      <p><strong>Miscellaneous Loss (dB)</strong> &mdash; additional cable / connector / combiner losses
      (&minus;10&hellip;+20&nbsp;dB, default 0). Added on top of the standard branching loss.</p>

      <p><strong>Reliability Method</strong> &mdash; selects the multipath outage model. Three options:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Vigants-Barnett</strong> &mdash; classic North American model. Shows a <em>C Factor</em>
            panel with preset buttons (Mtn = 0.25, Avg = 1.0, Water = 4.0) and a free-entry numeric field.
            A second panel lets you enter a <em>Climatic factor c<sub>f</sub></em> (Dry 0.5 / Avg 1.0 / Wet 2.0)
            and use the <strong>&#127758; Auto C from map</strong> button, which (i)&nbsp;estimates c<sub>f</sub>
            from the site coordinates (climate zone) and (ii)&nbsp;derives terrain roughness S from the loaded
            terrain profile, then computes C automatically using C&nbsp;=&nbsp;c<sub>f</sub>&middot;(S/15.2)^&minus;1.3.</li>
        <li><strong>ITU-R P.530-7/8</strong> &mdash; international standard with path-type selector:
            <em>Inland</em> (Eq.29), <em>Coastal / Large body of water</em> (Eq.30) or
            <em>Coastal / Medium body of water</em> (Eq.31).
            For coastal types an <em>Over-water fraction r<sub>c</sub></em> field (0&ndash;1) appears.
            The geoclimatic factor K is entered manually or auto-calculated (see below).</li>
        <li><strong>ITU-R P.530-17</strong> &mdash; same K / &epsilon;<sub>p</sub> inputs as P.530-7/8 but uses
            the updated distance exponent (d^3.6 vs d^3.0), giving more conservative results on longer paths.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Geoclimatic factor K</strong> (P.530-7/8 &amp; P.530-17) &mdash; enter manually as a number
      or in scientific notation (e.g. <code>1e-4</code>), or press the <strong>&#128205; Auto</strong> button
      to calculate K from the pinned site coordinates using ITU-R P.530-7/8 Eq.29:</p>
      <p><code>K = 5&times;10&#8315;&#8311; &middot; 10^(&minus;0.1(C&#8320;&minus;C<sub>Lat</sub>&minus;C<sub>Lon</sub>)) &middot; P<sub>L</sub>^1.5</code></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>C&#8320;</strong>: from the <em>Lower Antenna Altitude</em> (&lt;400 / 400&ndash;700 / &gt;700&nbsp;m ASL)
            &times; <em>Terrain Type</em> (Plains / Hills / Mountains) lookup table (ITU-R P.530-7/8 Table&nbsp;1).
            Auto-filled from terrain data when available.</li>
        <li><strong>C<sub>Lat</sub></strong>: 0 for |lat|&le;53°; linear ramp to 7 at |lat|=60°.</li>
        <li><strong>C<sub>Lon</sub></strong>: +3 Europe/Africa; &minus;3 Americas; 0 elsewhere.</li>
        <li><strong>P<sub>L</sub></strong>: % of worst month with refractivity gradient &lt;&minus;100&nbsp;N-units/km,
            approximated from latitude (tropical ~50%; sub-tropical ~30%; temperate ~20%; high-lat ~15%).</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Path Inclination |&epsilon;<sub>p</sub>|</strong> &mdash; auto-computed from antenna heights plus
      terrain end-point elevations: <code>|h<sub>t</sub>&minus;h<sub>r</sub>| / d</code> (mrad). The hint line
      shows the computed value (e.g. <em>Auto: 3.45&nbsp;mrad</em>). Enter a number to override manually; clear
      the field to revert to auto.</p>

      <h3>&#128200; Max-modulation caps (MW products)</h3>
      <p>The modulation list shown for each product is automatically capped to the maximum modulation that product
      supports at the selected channel BW and frequency band. All profiles from the lowest (BPSK / QPSK) up to
      and including the cap are shown; profiles above the cap are hidden. The rules are:</p>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><th>Condition</th><th>Max modulation</th></tr>
        <tr><td>BW 3.5 or 5&nbsp;MHz &mdash; all products</td><td>256QAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>BW 7 or 10&nbsp;MHz &mdash; all products</td><td>1KHQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IP-20C / IP-20C-HP, BW 14&nbsp;MHz</td><td>1KHQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IP-20C / IP-20C-HP, BW 20&ndash;80&nbsp;MHz</td><td>2KQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IP-50C / IP-50CX, BW 14 / 20 / 25&nbsp;MHz</td><td>2KQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IP-50C / IP-50CX, BW 50 or 56&nbsp;MHz, band &le;26&nbsp;GHz</td><td>4KQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IP-50C / IP-50CX, BW 50 or 56&nbsp;MHz, band &ge;28&nbsp;GHz</td><td>2KQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IP-50C / IP-50CX, BW 28 / 30 / 40 / 80 / 112&nbsp;MHz, band &le;32&nbsp;GHz</td><td>4KQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IP-50C / IP-50CX, BW 28 / 30 / 40 / 80 / 112&nbsp;MHz, band 38 or 42&nbsp;GHz</td><td>2KQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>IP-50C / IP-50CX, BW 224&nbsp;MHz</td><td>2KQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>RFU-D / RFU-D-HP, BW 14 or 20&nbsp;MHz</td><td>1KHQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>RFU-D / RFU-D-HP, BW 25&ndash;60&nbsp;MHz, all bands</td><td>2KQAM (4KQAM blocked)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>RFU-D / RFU-D-HP, BW 80 or 112&nbsp;MHz, band &le;32&nbsp;GHz</td><td>2KQAM</td></tr>
        <tr><td>RFU-D / RFU-D-HP, BW 80 or 112&nbsp;MHz, band 38 or 42&nbsp;GHz</td><td>1KHQAM</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h3 id="h-antennas">&#128301; Antennas</h3>
      <p>Pick a dish diameter for <strong>Site A</strong> and <strong>Site B</strong>. Larger dishes give higher
      gain (longer reach / more margin) but are heavier and have a narrower beam. The gain value used is shown
      next to the selector.</p>
      <p><strong>Additional Branching Loss</strong> accounts for losses in waveguide, couplers and combiners.
      A base value is set automatically from the configuration (1+0 vs 2+0 vs remote-mount); you can add extra
      dB on top.</p>
      <p><strong>Antenna heights (m AGL)</strong> default to <strong>50&nbsp;m</strong> above ground level for
      both sites. The Optimise Heights function computes the minimum heights for 60&nbsp;% Fresnel clearance
      when terrain data is available.</p>

      <h3 id="h-path">&#127783;&#65039; Path &amp; Rain</h3>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><th>Control</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Distance</td><td>Hop length. Set manually or auto-filled when both sites are pinned on the map.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>&#128207; Max</td><td>Panel showing the maximum range for each modulation and target availability,
            given the current radio, antenna and rain settings.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Rain Zone</td><td>ITU-R rain region (A&ndash;Q) or <strong>Manual</strong> for a custom rate.
            <strong>From Map</strong> uses the fetched ITU-R P.837-8 rain rate.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Target Availability</td><td>Yearly uptime target (e.g. 99.995&nbsp;% &asymp; 26&nbsp;min/yr downtime).
            The tool compares every modulation&apos;s predicted availability against this target.</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h3 id="h-site">&#127757; Site Location &amp; Climate (map)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pin sites</strong> &mdash; type a city in the Site A / Site B search box, or click on the map
            (1st click = A, 2nd = B). Distance appears automatically. Lat/lon can also be typed directly, or
            switched to degrees-minutes-seconds with the <code>DD&#8644;DMS</code> toggle.</li>
        <li><strong>&#8593; Peak search radius</strong> &mdash; default <strong>500&nbsp;m</strong>. The
            <em>&#8593;&nbsp;Peak</em> button finds the highest ground within this radius, useful for picking mast
            locations.</li>
        <li><strong>&#8635; Terrain profile</strong> &mdash; fetches the elevation profile and draws the line-of-sight
            with the 60&nbsp;% Fresnel zone. After loading, terrain roughness S is automatically computed for
            the VB C-factor and the lower antenna altitude is auto-filled for K calculation.</li>
        <li><strong>&#9650; Optimise Heights</strong> &mdash; auto-computes minimum antenna heights for 60&nbsp;%
            Fresnel clearance.</li>
        <li><strong>&#127760; Fetch Climate</strong> &mdash; pulls temperature, pressure, humidity, water-vapour
            density and ITU-R P.837-8 rain rate for the site coordinates.</li>
        <li><strong>&#9989; Apply to Link Budget</strong> &mdash; pushes the fetched atmosphere and rain rate
            into the calculation.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 id="h-sd">&#128268; Space Diversity (SD)</h3>
      <p>Space Diversity places a <strong>second receive antenna</strong> vertically below the main antenna on the
      same tower. The two signals are combined digitally (IFC 3&nbsp;dB combining), reducing the outage probability
      when ground-reflected multipath is the dominant impairment.</p>
      <div class="help-note"><strong>Eligibility:</strong> SD is available only for <strong>RFU-D, RFU-D-HP</strong>
      and <strong>IP-20C-HP</strong> at <strong>4, 5, 6, 7, 8 and 11&nbsp;GHz</strong>. The card is hidden for all
      other products and bands.</div>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Description</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Enable SD</td><td>Toggle to activate SD improvement. When off the diversity antenna is not drawn and the I_SD improvement is not applied.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Vertical separation (m)</td><td>Centre-to-centre distance between main and diversity antennas on the same tower. Default <strong>12&nbsp;m</strong>. Must be &ge; 2&nbsp;m.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>I_SD (improvement)</td><td>Space diversity improvement factor applied to the multipath outage probability.
            Formula (Vigants, ITU P.530-8 Eq.&nbsp;23):<br>
            <code>I_SD = 1.2&times;10&#8315;&sup3; &times; (f/d) &times; S&sup2; &times; v&sup2; &times; 10^(A/10)</code><br>
            where f = GHz, d = km, S = separation (m), v = 1, A = flat fade margin for that modulation.<br>
            A badge showing the I_SD multiplier appears next to the separation field.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Diversity antenna display</td><td>When SD is enabled the terrain profile shows the main antenna (blue/amber triangles) and the diversity antenna (green triangles) with a dashed vertical bar labelled with the separation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Reflection analysis (◆)</td><td>Shows the specular reflection point on the terrain for all four diversity path combinations, with the phase difference ΔΦ between the direct and reflected rays. The separation sweep table (8–20&nbsp;m) highlights separations where ΔΦ exceeds 150° (GOOD), helping optimise tower placement to minimise constructive reflections.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>k-factor chart</td><td>Plots the smooth-earth two-ray signal level vs the k-factor (0.3–15) for all four path combinations, showing how the earth&apos;s effective radius modifies the reflection geometry.</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h3 id="h-xpd">&#128225; Co-channel XPD / XPIC</h3>
      <p>Co-channel (same frequency, opposite polarisation) operation is used in <strong>2+0, 2+2 and 4+0</strong>
      configurations to double capacity in the same channel. The cross-polarisation discrimination (XPD) of the
      antennas and the optional XPIC canceller determine the carrier-to-interference (C/I) ratio.</p>
      <div class="help-note"><strong>Availability:</strong> The XPD card appears only when the configuration is
      <strong>2+0, 2+2 or 4+0</strong>. It is hidden for 1+0 and 1+1.</div>

      <p><strong>Inputs</strong></p>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Description</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Antenna XPD (dB)</td><td>Minimum boresight XPD of the Tx and Rx antennas. Default <strong>30&nbsp;dB</strong>. Applied symmetrically.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>XPIC device</td><td>Toggle on if an XPIC (Cross-Polarisation Interference Canceller) is fitted. The tool looks up the product-specific XPIF improvement factor per modulation and bandwidth from the Ceragon XPIF table.</td></tr>
      </table>

      <p><strong>Calculation chain (ITU-R P.530-8 / Vigants, K_XP = 0.7 single Tx)</strong></p>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><th>Step</th><th>Formula</th><th>Note</th></tr>
        <tr><td>XPD₀</td><td>XPDg+5 if XPDg&le;35, else 40</td><td>Adjusted antenna XPD (Eq.&nbsp;33)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>P₀</td><td>pM &times; 10^(EFM/10)</td><td>Fade occurrence factor (%)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>&eta;</td><td>1&minus;exp(&minus;0.2&middot;P₀^0.75)</td><td>Multipath activity factor (Eq.&nbsp;34)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q</td><td>&minus;10&middot;log&#8321;&#8320;(0.7&middot;&eta;/P₀)</td><td>XPD multipath protection (Eq.&nbsp;35)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C</td><td>XPD₀ + Q</td><td>Net protection ratio under clear sky (Eq.&nbsp;38)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C/I&nbsp;mph (no XPIC)</td><td>&minus;10&middot;log&#8321;&#8320;(2&middot;10^(&minus;XPDg/10) + 10^(&minus;(C&minus;A)/10)) + 2</td><td>Eq.&nbsp;39; A = flat fade margin</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C/I&nbsp;mph (+XPIC)</td><td>&minus;10&middot;log&#8321;&#8320;(10^(&minus;XPDg/10) + 2&middot;10^(&minus;(XPDg+XPIF)/10) + 10^(&minus;(C+XPIF&minus;A)/10)) + 2</td><td>Eq.&nbsp;40</td></tr>
        <tr><td>XPD_RAIN</td><td>15+30&middot;log f &minus; 12.8&middot;f^0.19&middot;log A₀.₀₁ (f&le;20&nbsp;GHz)<br>15+30&middot;log f &minus; 22.6&middot;log A₀.₀₁ (f&gt;20&nbsp;GHz)</td><td>Rain-induced XPD degradation (Eq.&nbsp;41)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C/I&nbsp;rain (no XPIC)</td><td>&minus;10&middot;log&#8321;&#8320;(2&middot;10^(&minus;XPDg/10) + 10^(&minus;XPD_RAIN/10)) + 2</td><td>Eq.&nbsp;42</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C/I&nbsp;rain (+XPIC)</td><td>&minus;10&middot;log&#8321;&#8320;(10^(&minus;XPDg/10) + 2&middot;10^(&minus;(XPDg+XPIF)/10) + 10^(&minus;(XPD_RAIN+XPIF)/10)) + 2</td><td>Eq.&nbsp;42 with XPIC</td></tr>
      </table>
      <p><strong>Interpreting C/I results:</strong>
      <span style="background:#d1fae5;color:#065f46;padding:2px 6px;border-radius:3px;font-weight:600">&ge;20&nbsp;dB</span>&nbsp;Comfortable margin &nbsp;
      <span style="background:#fef3c7;color:#92400e;padding:2px 6px;border-radius:3px;font-weight:600">10–20&nbsp;dB</span>&nbsp;Marginal — check with XPIC &nbsp;
      <span style="background:#fee2e2;color:#991b1b;padding:2px 6px;border-radius:3px;font-weight:600">&lt;10&nbsp;dB</span>&nbsp;Interference dominated — XPIC required or link redesign.
      </p>
      <p><strong>XPIF lookup:</strong> the XPIF (XPIC improvement factor, dB) is looked up automatically from the
      Ceragon product table for the active product family and the nearest channel bandwidth entry. Two families are
      defined: <em>IP-20C / IP-20C-HP</em> (BW 3.5–80&nbsp;MHz, QPSK–2KQAM) and
      <em>RFU-D / RFU-D-HP / IP-50C / IP-50CX</em> (BW 3.5–224&nbsp;MHz, BPSK–4KQAM).</p>

      <h3 id="h-results">&#128203; Reading the results</h3>
      <p>The status panel at the top shows the <strong>best modulation</strong> that meets the availability target,
      the associated capacity, RSL, fade margin and outage seconds. The <strong>Modulation Performance table</strong>
      lists every modulation profile with TX power, RSL threshold, flat and effective fade margin, rain outage,
      multipath outage, combined availability and capacity. Rows are colour-coded:
      <span style="color:#059669;font-weight:600">green</span> = meets target,
      <span style="color:#d97706;font-weight:600">amber</span> = within 0.5&nbsp;%,
      <span style="color:#dc2626;font-weight:600">red</span> = below target.</p>

      <h3 id="h-charts">&#128203; Tables &amp; charts</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Capacity vs Availability</strong> &mdash; each point is the real availability of a modulation
            at the current link distance.</li>
        <li><strong>Distance vs Availability</strong> &mdash; availability vs distance for every modulation.
            The red dashed line is your target; the navy dashed line is the current distance.
            X-axis options: 5, 10, 15, 20, 30, 50, <strong>80, 100, 150&nbsp;km</strong> (new).
            Y-axis: 95&nbsp;% &ndash; <strong>100&nbsp;%</strong> on a log-outage scale; curves flatten and
            pin to the 100&nbsp;% gridline when outage approaches zero.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 id="h-export">&#128190; Export &amp; theme</h3>
      <p><strong>Export to Excel</strong> saves the full link budget, modulation table and distance/availability
      sweep to an <code>.xlsx</code> workbook. The <strong>&#9790; / &#9728; toggle</strong> in the header
      switches between light and dark themes.</p>

      <h3 id="h-method">&#128214; Methodology &amp; references</h3>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><th>Recommendation</th><th>Used for</th></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.530-17</td><td>Multipath fading model (default MW method). Also used for rain outage probability formula (§2.3.1).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.530-18</td><td>Rain path reduction factor (frequency-dependent). Base: d<sub>0</sub> = 35·exp(&minus;0.015·R). P.530-18 applies a frequency correction χ(f) ≥ 1: d<sub>0,eff</sub> = d<sub>0</sub>/χ(f), d<sub>eff</sub> = d/(1+d/d<sub>0,eff</sub>). χ=1.0 below ~10&nbsp;GHz (same as P.530-16); χ=1.145 at 19&nbsp;GHz; χ=1.777 at 37&nbsp;GHz; χ=2.583 at 80&nbsp;GHz. Higher χ → shorter effective rain path → less predicted attenuation → better availability at medium and long distances. Significant improvement over P.530-16 for all bands ≥ 19&nbsp;GHz, especially E-band (70/80&nbsp;GHz).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.530-7/8</td><td>Earlier multipath model, selectable for MW links.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.838-3</td><td>Specific rain attenuation coefficients k and &alpha;.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.837-8</td><td>Rain rate R&#8320;.&#8320;&#8321; from map coordinates.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.676-12</td><td>Gaseous (O&#8322; + H&#8322;O) atmospheric attenuation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.835</td><td>Standard reference atmosphere (when no site climate is fetched).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.453</td><td>Reference for P<sub>L</sub> (refractivity gradient maps) used in K calculation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Vigants-Barnett</td><td>North American multipath model (Pathloss Eq.14&ndash;16).</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h3>&#128225; Multipath reliability formulas</h3>
      <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text2);line-height:1.6;margin:6px 0">
        Rain outage uses the flat fade margin (FFM = RSL<sub>unfaded</sub> &minus; RSL<sub>threshold</sub>).
        Multipath outage uses the <em>effective</em> fade margin (EFM), which combines the flat and dispersive
        components:</p>
      <p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--text2);margin:6px 0">
        <code>EFM = &minus;10&middot;log&#8321;&#8320;(10^(&minus;FFM/10) + 10^(&minus;DFM/10))</code></p>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><th>Method</th><th>Worst-month multipath outage p<sub>w</sub> (%)</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Vigants-Barnett</td><td>
          <code>P = 6&times;10&#8315;&#8311; &middot; C &middot; f &middot; d&sup3; &middot; 10^(&minus;EFM/10) &times; 100</code><br>
          C = 0.25 (mountainous/dry) &middot; 1.0 (average) &middot; 4.0 (over-water/coastal).<br>
          Auto-C: C = c<sub>f</sub> &middot; (S/15.2)^&minus;1.3, where S = terrain roughness (6&ndash;42&nbsp;m) from
          profile, c<sub>f</sub> = climate factor (0.5 dry, 1.0 avg, 2.0 humid).
        </td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.530-7/8<br><em>Inland</em></td><td>
          <code>K &middot; d&sup3; &middot; f^0.89 &middot; (1+|&epsilon;<sub>p</sub>|)^&minus;1.4 &middot; 10^(&minus;EFM/10)</code><br>
          K from Eq.29; d in km, f in GHz, &epsilon;<sub>p</sub> in mrad.
        </td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.530-7/8<br><em>Coastal large water</em></td><td>
          K from Eq.30: blends K<sub>i</sub> (inland) and K<sub>cl</sub> using over-water fraction r<sub>c</sub>.<br>
          K<sub>cl</sub> = 2.3&times;10&#8315;&#8308; &middot; 10^(&minus;0.1C&#8320; &minus; 0.011|r<sub>c</sub>|)
        </td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.530-7/8<br><em>Coastal medium water</em></td><td>
          K from Eq.31: blends K<sub>i</sub> and K<sub>cm</sub> using r<sub>c</sub>.<br>
          K<sub>cm</sub> = geometric mean of K<sub>i</sub> and K<sub>cl</sub>.
        </td></tr>
        <tr><td>ITU-R P.530-17</td><td>
          Same formula but with exponent d^3.6 instead of d^3.0 &mdash; more conservative for longer paths.
        </td></tr>
      </table>
      <p style="font-size:11.5px;color:var(--text3);line-height:1.55;margin:6px 0">
        Branching loss uses the direct-mount table for antennas &le;&nbsp;6&nbsp;ft/1.8&nbsp;m and the
        remote-mount table above that; the Miscellaneous-Loss field is added on top.
      </p>

      <h3 id="h-glossary">&#128218; Glossary</h3>
      <table class="help-deftable">
        <tr><td>RSL</td><td>Received Signal Level. The RSL <em>threshold</em> is the minimum power the receiver needs for a given modulation / BER.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FSL</td><td>Free-Space Loss &mdash; signal loss from spreading over distance.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FFM</td><td>Flat Fade Margin &mdash; dB headroom against thermal noise fading.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>DFM</td><td>Dispersive Fade Margin &mdash; equipment signature depth against selective fading.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>EFM</td><td>Effective Fade Margin &mdash; FFM and DFM combined (used for multipath outage).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ACM</td><td>Adaptive Coding &amp; Modulation &mdash; link automatically shifts to a more robust profile during fades.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C Factor</td><td>Vigants-Barnett terrain/climate factor: 0.25 (dry/rough) to 4.0 (flat/water).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>K</td><td>Geoclimatic factor in ITU-R P.530 &mdash; captures location-specific multipath severity.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>&epsilon;<sub>p</sub></td><td>Path inclination (mrad) &mdash; elevation angle between the two antenna ends.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>S</td><td>Terrain roughness (m) &mdash; standard deviation of elevation samples along the path profile.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>P<sub>L</sub></td><td>% of worst month with refractivity gradient &lt;&minus;100&nbsp;N-units/km (ITU-R P.453).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>WVD</td><td>Water-Vapour Density (g/m&sup3;) &mdash; humidity term in atmospheric loss.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>R&#8320;.&#8320;&#8321;</td><td>Rain rate (mm/h) exceeded 0.01&nbsp;% of an average year.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>AGL</td><td>Above Ground Level &mdash; antenna mounting height.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>ASL</td><td>Above Sea Level &mdash; absolute altitude, used for geoclimatic K calculation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Fresnel zone</td><td>Elliptical region around the line of sight that must stay clear of obstacles (target: 60&nbsp;% clearance).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Availability</td><td>Percentage of the year the link meets its performance target.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>SD</td><td>Space Diversity — second receive antenna on the same tower, vertically offset, used to mitigate ground-reflected multipath on low-band (4–11&nbsp;GHz) links.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>I_SD</td><td>Space Diversity improvement factor — divisor applied to the multipath outage probability when SD is enabled (Vigants Eq.&nbsp;23).</td></tr>
        <tr><td>XPD</td><td>Cross-Polarisation Discrimination (dB) — measure of how well an antenna rejects the opposite polarisation. Higher = less co-channel interference.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>XPIC</td><td>Cross-Polarisation Interference Canceller — DSP device that cancels cross-polar interference. Provides XPIF dB of improvement.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>XPIF</td><td>XPIC Improvement Factor (dB) — product- and modulation-specific benefit of the XPIC device, from Ceragon test data.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C/I</td><td>Carrier-to-Interference ratio (dB) — protection against cross-polar signal. Computed per modulation for multipath (Eq.&nbsp;39/40) and rain (Eq.&nbsp;42) conditions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>XPD₀</td><td>Adjusted antenna XPD used in the co-channel calculation: XPDg+5 if XPDg≤35&nbsp;dB, else 40&nbsp;dB (ITU P.530-8 Eq.&nbsp;33).</td></tr>
      </table>

    </div>

    <div class="help-foot">
      Planning estimates only &mdash; verify against the equipment datasheet and a field survey before deployment.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
function openHelp(){
  var ov=document.getElementById('helpOverlay');
  ov.classList.add('open');
  var b=document.getElementById('helpBody'); if(b) b.scrollTop=0;
  // Clear search on open
  var inp=document.getElementById('helpSearchInput');
  if(inp){inp.value='';helpSearch('');}
  document.body.style.overflow='hidden';
  setTimeout(function(){if(inp)inp.focus();},120);
}

// ── Help search: highlight matching text in help body ────────────────────────
function helpSearch(query){
  const body=document.getElementById('helpBody');
  const cnt=document.getElementById('helpSearchCount');
  if(!body) return;
  // Remove previous highlights
  body.querySelectorAll('mark.help-hl').forEach(m=>{
    m.replaceWith(document.createTextNode(m.textContent));
  });
  body.normalize();
  if(!query||query.trim().length<2){if(cnt)cnt.textContent='';return;}
  const q=query.trim();
  const re=new RegExp(q.replace(/[.*+?^${}()|[\]\\]/g,'\\$&'),'gi');
  let matchCount=0;
  function walkNode(node){
    if(node.nodeType===3){
      const txt=node.textContent;
      if(!re.test(txt)){re.lastIndex=0;return;}
      re.lastIndex=0;
      const frag=document.createDocumentFragment();
      let last=0,m;
      while((m=re.exec(txt))!==null){
        if(m.index>last) frag.appendChild(document.createTextNode(txt.slice(last,m.index)));
        const mark=document.createElement('mark');
        mark.className='help-hl';
        mark.textContent=m[0];
        frag.appendChild(mark);
        matchCount++;
        last=m.index+m[0].length;
      }
      if(last<txt.length) frag.appendChild(document.createTextNode(txt.slice(last)));
      node.parentNode.replaceChild(frag,node);
    } else if(node.nodeType===1 && !['SCRIPT','STYLE','INPUT'].includes(node.tagName)){
      Array.from(node.childNodes).forEach(walkNode);
    }
  }
  walkNode(body);
  if(cnt)cnt.textContent=matchCount?matchCount+' match'+(matchCount>1?'es':''):'no match';
  // Scroll to first highlight
  const first=body.querySelector('mark.help-hl');
  if(first) first.scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'center'});
}
